  "prompt": "What is the difference between constitutional and statutory bodies or powers in India?",
  "response": "Here are the key differences between constitutional and statutory bodies in India:\n\nConstitutional Bodies:\n1. Established directly by the Constitution\n2. Cannot be abolished by ordinary legislation\n3. Powers and functions defined in the Constitution\n4. More permanent and autonomous\n5. Examples: Election Commission, CAG, UPSC\n\nStatutory Bodies:\n1. Created by specific acts of Parliament\n2. Can be modified or abolished by legislative process\n3. Powers and functions defined in the parent act\n4. Less permanent and more flexible\n5. Examples: TRAI, SEBI, National Human Rights Commission\n\nKey Distinctions:\n- Constitutional bodies have constitutional protection\n- Statutory bodies derive authority from specific laws\n- Constitutional bodies have more inherent autonomy\n- Statutory bodies can be more easily restructured\n\nBoth types play important roles in governance, but constitutional bodies generally have higher constitutional status and greater independence.",
